**Description**

In RuntimeAsync, `await Task.Yeild()` does not currently generate sufficient debug information.  

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Compile a program with RuntimeAsync enabled with this function in it:
```csharp
static async Task TaskReturningMethodAsync(bool syncReturn)
{
    if (syncReturn)
        return;

    await Task.Yield();
}
```
When stepping through the function with `syncReturn` =`true`, we noticed that stepping over the `return` statement, execution jumped to the last line of the function which is not being executed.    

<img width="780" height="140" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/39a9a660-01e9-4a8d-a6ae-26dbeffe81de" />

The issue is that the return statement jumps to ret at the end of the function, which doesn't have any sequence points for it.  This causes the debugger to attribute the IL offset of the ret instruction at the end of the method to the `await Task.Yield()` statement.  

**Expected Behavior**

Given the following:

```csharp
await Task.Yield();
```

The compiler should generate: 

```csharp
var tmp = Task.Yield().GetAwaiter();
// Sequence point for this branch
if (!tmp.IsCompleted)
    AsyncHelpers.UnsafeAwaitAwaiter(tmp);
tmp.Result;
```

**Actual Behavior**

No sequence point data is generated for `await Task.Yield();`

**Version Used**: 

.NET 11 Preview 1

